These menacing multi-legged minions come in a variety of scales, as originally sculpted, but their universal nature and lack of scale cues enables them to be used as massed armies in nearly any setting, and can be exchanged easily between settings. A 28mm spiderdrone looks impressive next to a 15mm human, while the 6mm spiderbots look like they can crawl over and pull down a 28mm figure.

The 28mm, multi-part versions are crafted in separate legs and blasters set at multiple angles. The 15mm and 6mm versions are tiny and fused. You can fill entire print beds with the little creepy-crawlers!

Originally created as escort bots and onboard infantry for the ScorpionMech, which I also offer, these little bots come in deployed and stowed versions, with full and empty carrier racks that can be adapted to other builds.

ScorpionMechs and other figures are shown for reference, and are sold separately.

Enjoy!

Best,

JBR

Ten unique poses with the original style armor and weapons, fully kitted out with drum mag bolters, heavy bolter, heavy flamer, melta gun, plasma gun, flamer, and a sergeant with power sword and pistol. Ordnance options include a grenade launcher and missile launchers.

Enjoy!

A humble reworking of Moonjammy's excellent designs, optimised for stackable printing.

Love printing little dudes but hate having to get up every hour to scrape off your build plate, waste good resin in your wash station, and restart the print? Then here's the new easy-to-use stacking solution you've been waiting for! Stack small objects vertically to fit into your print schedule, or efficiently fill left over build plate volume when printing taller objects.

Including:
- **Galactic Crusader Infantry with Jump Jets** in 2egmented, 3oarding, and Pl4te armour
- Arranged in pre-built stacks of 20, 30 and 40.
- Raw components and a guide for creating custom stacks

**Scale and Sizing:**
The Galactic Crusaders in this pack have been resized to 105%.
This makes the average Galactic Crusader ~9.5mm tall (varying based on pose and armour style), and the base plugs 6.16x1.31mm.

**Want to know more about Floating Rafts and you can use them to convert your own models into stackable designs?**
Check out the [Floating Raft Stackable Conversion System](https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/art/starports-floating-rafts-stackable-conversion-system)!

*Like what I'm doing? [Buy me a cup of resin!](https://ko-fi.com/lstar)*

How hungry are they?
So hungry they could eat an entire planet.

Variety of chainaxe wielding maniacs in segmented armour pattern.
Comes with regular helm, Sarum helm, and Hungry Boys Veteran helm for all pose types.

Extra variety can be gotten by mirroring the various poses. In particular with the dual and two-handed chainaxe variants.

For the flying marines, they have holes in the jump pack to accept a 1mm rod as a flight stand. For my example (see my generic assault marines), I cut halfway along the curve of a paperclip, inserted the curved end into the hole with a bit of superglue and adjusted the tilt of the marine from there. Then, drill a hole into your base of choice, and adjust the height of the paperclip as desired.

There is also a "_standoffs" version. This is something I'm playing around with where the models' feet are offset from the plug, allowing you to use the plug as a stand when painting, and then slice or snip off the small cylinders to allow you to glue the feet directly onto the base, for a seamless finish.

If you'd rather adjust the placement of the rods yourself for use with straight brass rod, or clear acrylic rods, I've provided the "_nohole" versions for this purpose.

Thanks to Moonjammy for the excellent original models!

If you like what I'm doing, please donate to my Ko-Fi!
https://ko-fi.com/daffmakes

+++ Berserks units are made up from assault squads of the mos ferocious hand-to-hand fighters in the Stronghold. Armed with bolt pistols and power axes, theyre experts tunnel fighters and excel at clearing buildings and fortifications ahead of the Brotherhoods advance. All squats are doughty fighters in close combat, but the Berserks units are renowed for their tneacity and courage against even the mightiest opponents without thought for their own looses.

By tradition, Berserkers often wear a striking crest dyed bright red, which is why they refuse to wear combat helmets. The origins of this practice have been lost in the mists of time, but what for many Imperial officers could be an absurd and tactically reprehensible risk, for the Squats is definitive proof of the courage of the Berserkers and their attitude of always spitting in deaths face.+++

I have had these models ready for quite some time, and in fact I also have them printed, but due to lack of time I have not been able to mount and paint them properly to take nice pics.

As I am currently focused on finishing my squat miners (among other lesser things such as graduating from university), I don't think I will resume my Epic Squats in the short term, so I have decided to upload these Berserkers models once and for all and thus finish the infantry forces at least.

Finally this guys come in two flavours: with a boltpistol/power axe combo, and the classic dual wield boltpistols. This is a simple aestetic choice to give variety to the squads.

+++ Traditionally the elite warriors known as the Hearthguards accompany the Warlord as his personal bodyguards, however their duties do not end there. Hearthguards who are not in the direct service of the Warlord take the position of platoon "captains", leading troops directly into battle. Only when a Hearthguard has proven to be a charismatic leader, a resourceful strategist, and a skilled warrior, he can be considered to be part of the Warlord's personal guard in the future.

The Hearthguards go into battle accompanied by an retinue of warriors selected from among the most skilled and trusted veterans, as they carry valuable weapons known as "heirloom weapons." These weapons are evidence of the maximum skill of the squat artificers, surpassing in every aspect their more common equivalents, and many of them have been in service of the squat noble families for centuries and some even millennia. +++

This is a Squat Hearthguard unit designed for NetEpic Armageddon, in specific for the Grindel Sronghold army list that you can find here: https://tacticalwargames.net/taccmd/viewtopic.php?f=134&t=33281&sid=422418b4bea515739e1aef8d862588e5

+++ The individuals known as Grand Warlords are rarely seen, appearing only in the largest of battles where their great tactical skill and commanding presence are necessary to control a vast army of countless soldiers and monstrous war engines. The title itself is temporary, lasting for the duration of the campaign and generally being awarded to a warlord who stands out above the rest due to his martial achievements, although it is also possible that the Stronghold Lord himself is the one who wears the powerful Exo-armor distinctive of the Great Warlord. However, although it grants great honor and renown, it is a position that implies tremendous responsibility that not everyone is willing to assume or able to fulfill, and for a Great Warlord defeat in battle means ruin and contempt for his clan for generations.

The Living Ancestors are the oldest individuals in Squat society, who form the basis of their religion. For all intents and purposes, the Living Ancestors have abandoned their previous life and identity and are now regarded as vessels of the spirits of the deceased, who observe and judge all the actions of the Squats. In battle they provide wisdom and advice for leaders, and physical support for warriors, because their long life (or perhaps also due to the influence of spirits) has allowed them to develop psychic powers which focus on defense and healing, but they are not completely incapable of attacking if they are forced to do so, although with much disgust. +++


These are a Epic scale Squat Grand Warlord and a Living Ancestor for the Grindel Sronghold army list that you can find here: https://tacticalwargames.net/taccmd/viewtopic.php?f=134&t=33281&sid=422418b4bea515739e1aef8d862588e5

They are considered characters, which means that they do not form individual units but must join an existing one. As you can see in the photos, I attached them to a Warlord unit, because I think it makes sense, but they are not restricted to this unit only.

A slightly unhinged reworking of Moonjammy's excellent design, optimised for _crazy_ printing!

A new concept for creating simple, stackable supports for Epic scale infantry! Create blocks of infantry in any arbitrary width and height simply by copying strips in Lychee and moving them vertically, no additional fine-tuning required!

**ARE STACKABLE SUPPORTS RIGHT FOR ME?**

Stackable supports are resin-inefficient compared with printing a single squad flat on the build plate, but time and clean-up efficient, allowing you to print large numbers of troops in a single print without having to get up to scrape them off the build plate, clean up, and restart your print every hour!

Stackable supports also allow you to make effective use of empty space on your build plate when printing larger vehicles or 28mm scale models. Just create a stack as tall as your other models!

**UH OH, THIS LOOKS COMPLICATED! IS REMOVING THE SUPPORTS HARD?**

De-supporting these is easy and risk free!
The heavy supports only make contact with the pseudo-rafts so you can yank them off without any worries. Then just use a knife tip or tweezer to pick off the remaining supports on the individual models.

**I THINK MARK 2s ARE STUPID! ARE YOU GOING TO SUPPORT OTHER TYPES OF INFANTRY?**

Probably! Eventually! But until I get round to it, feel free to try this style of supporting on your own models 

*Like what I'm doing? [Buy me a cup of resin!](https://ko-fi.com/lstar)*

The Empire of Sentient Man has the diverse army taking part in permament war against the foul traitors and treacherous aliens. Mostly, the army is represented by ill-equipped militia in various ballistic armour (including coats), wielding only laser rifles. Red Militia has such a tragic fate. While being the defenders of their land, they have to reach the planets too far beyond comprehension, test the mud with their boots and treads and hope for weapons to beat unfamiliar threats.

The Red Militia models, with faces diminished and bases added, are shared for free with the permission of NotANiceGuy (https://cults3d.com/en/users/NotANiceGuy/3d-models).

The pack contains:
- command squad including lieutenant, communication officer, standard bearer and sergeant;
- line infantry in 8 different poses;
- heavy weapons teams with heavy machine gun, automatic gun, laser cannon, missile launcher;
- random loaders and mortar crew;
- plus non-Red Militia 3 commissars and 2 psykers.

UPDATE 2023.08.15:
- added separate heavy weapons;
- improved missile launcher crew, version two added;
- mortars added.

UPDATE 2023.12.14:
- Master of Discipline model added;
- All the Red Militia are downscaled to fit 8mm scale;
- All the weapons on carriages are downscaled;
- New Missile Launcher team for nostalgic feels.

Pictures with resin prints of pre-release version of 8mm Red Militia models included. The current models have sturdier bases, and the standard bearer got thicker banner pole.

"'Ere We Go, 'Ere We Go, 'Ere We Go!"
 Common Ork chant heard during a Greenskin WAAAGH!
The Orks, also called Greenskins, are a savage, warlike, green-skinned race of humanoids who are spread all across the Milky Way Galaxy. They share many features with Warhammer Fantasy Orcs (and were initially called "Space Orcs" to distinguish them). They are seen by their enemies (pretty much everyone else in the universe) as savage, warlike, and crude, but they are the most successful species in the whole galaxy, outnumbering possibly every other intelligent race, even Mankind (with the very plausible exception of the Tyranids).

Greenskins are one of the most dangerous alien races to plague the galaxy. Numerous beyond belief and driven always to fight and conquer, the Orks threaten every single intelligent species of the galaxy. Orks are possibly the most warlike aliens in the 41st Millennium, and their number is beyond counting. Amid constant, seething tides of war and bloodshed, burgeoning Ork stellar empires rise and fall. Mercifully most are short-lived, soon destroying themselves in a maelstrom of violence and internecine conflict, but should the Orks ever truly unify, they would crush all opposition.

The Orks' unquenchable thirst for battle has always proved their downfall: historically, the Ork tribes have spent much of their time fighting amongst themselves, waging brutal wars with only the strongest surviving. On occasion, an Ork leader will emerge who is mighty enough to defeat his rivals and unite the warring tribes. His success draws other tribes to him, and soon a great WAAAGH! is underway -- partly a migration, partly a holy war that can exterminate the populations of entire star systems. When the Orks are on the rampage, the galaxy trembles, and in these dark days of the End Time, there are more WAAAGH!s rising than ever before recorded.

***THIS IS A WORK IN PROGRESS***

Tiny troops which are perfect for giving your games of epic conflict a sense of epic scale. And what can be more perfect than the golden perfect winged assault cherubs?

Building on the foundation that Moonjam left us, I've remodeled and rebuilt most of the base Galactic Crusader parts into higher detailed versions that will allow those of you with 8k and 12k printers to showcase your models with. In addition, the figures are easily to print at 200% (maybe even 400%?) for use with other games systems and scales.

The blender source is included containing my hobo-rigged figures and pose library. I wasn't feeling all too well and took some liberties/shortcuts than I would for a more generic release but should get you most of the way even when I used basic object parenting for a few parts. Sorry =/

Figures have been run through 3DBuilder to merge and decimate the meshes to reasonable levels though you can export your own from the Blend. I've also uploaded a zip of just the unmerged undecimated figures for your further use if so desired. Not that plinths, risers, and banner icons are NOT merged so you can rework or replace stuff as works for you.

Big shouts out to Moonjam for the base content to build on. Icons from Lord Chronos. Heads based on work from M3rcurymordbid.

If you like what I did and want to leave a tip it would be appreciated.

Inspired by EpicRich's work but a rebuild from the ground up for your Chaotic Elite needs. Figures come with helmets and unhelmeted forms.

FYI: As the original inspiration contained the customary 'chaos means spike rack' I've included an option for them but they may be a nightmare so versions of figures without are present as well (also they were designed for my 15mm Space Hulk needs anyways). The shoulder pads are a sin against all that is holy and LoggyK but done for expediency. Keep a watch here because I will build some custom pads in the future for GC chaos dudes.

Due to the numbers of remixes and various tooling used over the years, we'd seen many mesh errors and misalignments / bad rotations of parts creep into the base design. The Indomitus kit has been extensively worked over to be symmetrical and properly aligned now with all parts being cleaned and normalized.

Blender file source included as well for you to further customize your forces of disorder with.

edit 20221109: Updated the Lord with better posing and added a heavy weapon terminator

Demon beasts for warmaster both with and without supports using ADeco's awesome minotaur demon. I fattened its lower legs up a bit to keep them from breaking.

10mm demon army
See my collections for the other units; I have a unit for each of the roles in warmaster revolution and a couple of heroes. Note that this army does not inherently match one of the big four chaos gods by design, as I find them dreadfully boring.

Supports
The supports are auto generated by Prusa. To my surprise none of its horns broke off when removing supports, although you should try to be gentle.

Why?
I just got a 3d printer and was looking to get into warmaster with some friends when I noticed that there is no ready to print demon army yet. Given my 0-level modelling skills I instead decided to use existing models to create the army; this unit is one of the outcomes of this project.

Disclaimer
To be sure: none of these models are actually mine. I am a complete hack blundering his way through blender; all I can do is resize models, fatten segments and add cylinders (you may spot some of my handiwork on other models, or here!).

THESE ARE ENTIRELY UNOFFICIAL AND THIRD PARTY. NOTHING TO DO WITH MANTIC GAMES.

These are the custom parts I sculpted and got printed for my Kings of War Abyssals army. They are completely unofficial and are not produced, licensed or connected in any way to Mantic.

There are 3 files;
Arug - Head: A custom head for my Archfiend, Arug Or'Gal
Arug - Mace: A custom mace and right hand for my Archfiend model
Arug - Screaming Skull: This is a 3D version of my army logo that I used for objective markers

The head and mace will require conversion work for the archfiend model - you will need to trim away excess from both the custom part and the original and fill with greenstuff. They don't simply slot into place, you will need to do some chopping and converting.

For printing, I ordered through 3DHubs.com with a resin printer at max resolution.

Though playable with other outdated sets from this edition, this set is not compatible with the current edition of Pocket-Tactics. You can find all of the [current sets here on our site](https://www.illgottengames.net/products?category=Pocket-Tactics).

If you want to help us create more sets and expansions for the game (and get a bunch of 3d printables in the process) please consider supporting us on [Patreon](https://www.patreon.com/illgottengames)!

-------------------------------------------------RULES-------------------------------------------------------
For a standard 50 point build you'll want to build using a combination of units and spell cards. For a starting build, consider the following: Guild Initiate x1, Guild Apprentice x1, Guild Mage x1, Guild Guard x1, Grand Librarian x1 (totaling 32 points + 18 points worth of spell cards, Stonework tile x4, Water tile x2. The Fortress, Ruins, or Township features are good tactical/thematic choices for this build.

Inverted-color images of the rules cards are available [here](http://i.imgur.com/Du3YYXf.png), [here](http://i.imgur.com/S9i78Sg.png), [here](http://i.imgur.com/IMIMQly.png), and [here](http://i.imgur.com/QJlHoJQ.png) if you want something a little less ink-intensive.

SETTING UP

To begin, each player builds a force by selecting a number of units that total 50 points or less. For a larger game, you and your opponent could agree on a higher point total.

Next, each player chooses 6 tiles and all of the tiles are dropped into a bag and shuffled. Then, players agree (randomly, if you choose) on a central feature tile and then each choose a feature for themselves. (features are the 3-dimensional tiles such as Forest, Highlands, Villages, et cetera). Draw a single tile from the bag and place the central feature into that tile. Rolling off to see who goes first, players take turns drawing tiles from the bag and placing them adjacent to one another in whatever configuration they wish. Once all of the tiles have been placed, each player (in turn order decided by the roll-off) places their chosen feature so that it is both as many tiles away from the center and from one another as possible.

Once the map has been generated, players place up to three units of their choice (as many as they can fit) either in or adjacent to their chosen feature using the rolled-off turn order. You may only ever have a single unit occupy a tile or feature. Once this is finished, game play begins starting with the last player to place their units.

PLAYING THE GAME

Each turn, a player may either move one of their units, use one of their units to assault an enemy unit, or deploy a new unit onto the map.

MOVING: When activating a unit to move, they may do so into any unoccupied tile adjacent to them. If an allied unit is in an adjacent tile, the moving unit may hop over that unit to get to an open tile adjacent to their ally. A unit may only hop a single ally per move. Some features (Forests, Highlands, Villages, et cetera) have special movement considerations that will be listed on their rules card. Spaces that do not contain a tile may not be moved into.

SWIFT UNITS: Units with this symbol on their rules card may perform a number of bonus moves equal to the numeric value listed to the side when they are activated to move.

FLYING UNITS: Units with this symbol on their rules card may perform a number of bonus moves equal to the numeric value listed to the side when they are activated to move and may hop over enemy units as though they were allies when doing so.

ASSAULTS: When activating a unit to assault an adjacent enemy, each player tests their units Offense (OFF) by rolling their red dice and defense (DEF) by rolling their blue dice. A unit will have between zero and three of each kind of dice as shown on their rules cards. The assault occurs in three phases:

Roll Phase- All dice are rolled simultaneously.

Bump Phase- Some units have bumps, a numeric value with a + listed under either their OFF or DEF dice. Starting with the player initiating the assault, each player may take turns using a single bump. Each bump may adjust a single die result (either OFF or DEF) up by its value (though a single die may not go higher than 6). Some units may have multiple bump values listed under their dice or granted by special abilities or terrain effects.

Re-Roll Phase- Starting with the player initiating the assault, each player takes turns using any re-rolls they are afforded, either by special abilities or terrain/unit placement. Each re-roll allows the player to re-roll one of their die results (OFF or DEF). A unit that has adjacent allies is benefiting from support and gains one re-roll per ally. A unit also gains a single re-roll when occupying their favored terrain (a terrain tile or feature that is shown on their rules card).

Tally Phase- Each player checks their OFF results and checks them against the opponent's DEF results. Starting with the highest OFF die, compare it to the highest enemy DEF die. If the results are a tie, move on to the next highest. If a single OFF die can't be matched or beat by value from the enemy's DEF, that enemy is defeated and is removed from the map and placed in the victorious player's captures (a space to the side of the map on that player's side). If the OFF cannot beat the enemy DEF values, that unit is safe. Note that, because all dice are rolled at once, it is possible for both units to defeat one another simultaneously.

RANGED ATTACKS: Units with this symbol on their rules card may make assaults against units that are an extra number of tiles away equal to the numeric value listed to the side. Count through the closest route to get to the target before making a ranged assault. Features and enemy units block line of sight (except when a Flying unit is targeted or is making the assault) and empty spaces (spaces without a tile) always block line of sight. If a unit being assaulted is not capable of meeting the range requirements to the attacker, they may not roll their OFF dice for that assault.

DEPLOYMENT: In place of activating one of your units already on the map, you may choose a unit from your reserves (any of the units you didn't put on the map at the start of the game that haven't been captured by enemies) and place them adjacent to any feature on the map that you control (provided the space is unoccupied). If no such tile exists, you may not deploy a unit until one opens up.

Any player may, in place of performing a regular move action, move a piece into an occupied feature tile to return that unit to reserves. Similarly, a unit that is occupying a feature may move into that feature to return to reserves, though you then cede control of the feature by doing so.

TYPES

Listed directly beneath a unit's name are a number of types (Human, Elf, Robot, et cetera). These types have no effect on their own, though are referenced by certain abilities and terrain effects that may either be beneficial or detrimental to the unit.

HAZARDS

Some terrain tiles and features contain hazards. These are special effects that occur when a unit is moved into that tile. Units that are deployed into a tile with hazard effects ignore them, as do units that have that tile type as their favored terrain.

WATER: A unit moving into a Water tile must succeed at a DV 5 DEF test or be defeated immediately after doing so.

If a feature is placed in a terrain tile, the tile counts as that feature rather than the terrain type, and therefore negates any hazard effects native to the terrain type.

VICTORY CONDITIONS

A player achieves victory as soon as their opponent (or opponents) cannot activate or deploy any units. Alternately, victory is secured the moment any single player controls all features on the map.

USING SPELL CARDS

When using spell cards in your force, each card selected is subtracted from your force point total. For example, if your are including the Fireball spell (which costs 2 points as indicated at the bottom of the card) in a standard 50-point force, it takes up 2 of those 50 points. You may use any number of spell cards in your force build provided you can afford their point cost and may use duplicates of the same spell if you like.

At the start of the game, shuffle all of your spell cards into a deck, then draw up to five of them. At the start of each turn, you may draw back up to five if you have less than five cards in your hand. You may not have more than five cards in your hand at any time.

Any unit with the Mage type may use spell cards, following the instructions when doing so. After a spell card has been used, place it in a discard pile designated to the side of the deck. Discarded cards may not be used again (except with the use of special abilities like the 'Grand Grimoire' ability possessed by the Archmage).
